{"cursor":"8430","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox Weapon |name= M320 Grenade Launcher Module |image= |caption=\nStandalone M320 with detachable buttstock |origin= |type= Grenade launcher  |is_ranged=yes |is_bladed= |is_explosive= |is_artillery=\n|is_vehicle=  |service= 2009 to present |used_by= |wars=\n |designer= |design_date= 2008 |manufacturer=Heckler\n& Koch |unit_cost=US$3,500 |production_date= 2008 |number= |variants=  |weight=1.5 kg (3.3 lb) |length=350 mm (13.7 in.)\n|part_length=280 mm (11 in.)  |cartridge=\n40x46mm SR |action= Single shot, double action |rate= 5 to 7 rounds per minute\n|velocity= 76 m/s |range= 150 m |max_range= 400 m |feed= Single shot |sights=\n |breech= |recoil= |carriage= |elevation=\n|traverse=  |blade_type= |hilt_type=\n|head_type= |haft_type=  |diameter= |filling=\n|filling_weight= |detonation= |yield= }}\n\n'M320 Grenade Launcher Module' (GLM) is the U.S. military's designation for a\nnew single-shot 40 mm grenade launcher system to replace the M203 [https://peosoldier.army.mil/pmsw/index.asp\n\"Product Manager Individual Weapons\"] for the U.S. Army, while other\nservices will keep using the older M203. The M320 uses the same High-Low\nPropulsion System as the M203.\n\nAfter the U.S. Army at Picatinny Arsenal conducted a competitive bidding process\nfor a new 40Â mm grenade launching system, Heckler & Koch was awarded a\ncontract to provide the XM320 beginning in 2006. The M320 was developed from but\nis not identical to the Heckler & Koch AG36 (a key distinguishing feature being\nthe addition of a folding foregrip ahead of the trigger for use when the weapon\nis in stand-alone configuration, a feature the AG36 lacks). The M320 entered production in November 2008.\n\nThe unit was officially fielded in July 2009 at Fort Bragg by the 1st Brigade\nCombat Team, 82nd Airborne Division. MacLeod, Spc. Michael J. [http://www.military.com/news/article/army-news/bragg-gis-1st-to-field-grenade-\nlauncher.html?ESRC